oglia exposed to MPP+ and in MPTP-treated mice, miR-141-3p downregulates HMGB1, reduces pro-inflammatory cytokine readouts, and in vivo is associated with improved rotarod and open-field performance and attenuated Tyrosine Hydroxylase (TH)-positive neuronal loss. OMT increases miR-141-3p in the MPTP model, alongside reduced HMGB1 and inflammatory readouts, and these effects are diminished by miR-141-3p inhibition.\n\nCONCLUSION: miR-141-3p targets HMGB1 to inhibit microglial reaction and mitigate neuroinflammation both in vivo and vitro experiments, reduce TH-positive neuronal loss in the MPTP model. OMT increases miR-141-3p in the MPTP model, alongside reduced HMGB1 and inflammatory readouts, and these effects are diminished by miR-141-3p inhibition.", 'summary_1': ''}
